Case study report for Cardiotrophin-1

29 June 2022

Report for: Cardiotrophin-1 (prot-a-710)

This case study report includes the results for Cardiotrophin-1, generated automatically using Rmarkdown.

The report is split into 3(+1) parts:

  1. Mendelian randomization (MR) results for Cardiotrophin-1 for all breast cancer outcomes (BCAC 2017 and 2020)
  2. Overview of potential mediators identified from MR-EvE data; their validation with two-step and multivariable MR (MVMR)
  3. Overview of potential mediators identified from literature-mined data; their validation with two-step, bidirectional and MVMR
  4. Optional validation of results with female-only exposure data (if available)
  • Trait IDs in this report correspond to data available in OpenGWAS
  • BCAC 2017 outcomes names/IDs: Full sample ieu-a-1126, ER+ sample ieu-a-1127, ER- sample ieu-a-1128
  • MR analyses in this report were performed using TwoSampleMR and MVMR packages

This report is a part of publication “Integrating Mendelian randomization and literature-mined evidence for breast cancer risk factors” Vabistsevits et al 2022

1 Main MR results

Cardiotrophin-1 was identified in MR-EvE search as having evidence of effect on breast cancer and validated with IVW MR method in BCAC 2017 and BCAC 2020 breast cancer outcomes:

The full MR results and sensitivity analysis are available in Supplementary Data 2 and 3.

3 Literature-mined mediators

We searched literature-mined relationships in EpiGraphDB for Cardiotrophin-1 and breast cancer and used literature-overlap method to identify potential intermediates between the two. The identified intermediates are tested as potential mediaotrs in this section.

3.1 Summary

Cardiotrophin-1 literature space contains:

  • 136 unique triples of terms

  • 123 unique pairs of terms

3.3 Matching literature terms to GWAS traits

Cardiotrophin-1 and breast cancer literature space overlap identified:

  • 26 unique literature terms

  • 13 terms are available as GWAS traits in OpenGWAS (table below)

  • 9 (7 unique) traits have >=1 genome-wide significant SNPs (instruments for MR) (highlighted in the table)

3.4 Two-step MR (step 2)

We performed two-step MR for 9 traits with >=1 instruments (highlighted in table above):

  • RAC-alpha/beta/gamma serine/threonine-protein kinase
  • Leukemia inhibitory factor
  • Leukemia inhibitory factor receptor
  • Mitogen-activated protein kinase 1
  • Oncostatin-M
  • Signal transducer and activator of transcription 3
  • Vascular endothelial growth factor A
  • Pituitary adenylate cyclase-activating polypeptide

Out of these traits, 2 had evidence of effect on breast cancer (so could be considered further as potential mediators):

  • Leukemia inhibitory factor receptor
  • Leukemia inhibitory factor

3.5 Bidirectional MR (exp/med) (step1)

We next performed bidirectional MR to to establish the direction of the effect between the intermediate and the risk factor and identify the traits that are affected by the risk factor (i.e. likely mediator relationship) [Exposure -> mediator (step1 of two-step MR)] and the other way around (i.e. potential confounder relationship).
